article.description:
Chris Webber had 20 points and seven
assists, and Peja Stojakovic scored 18 points as the Sacramento
Kings stayed in the hunt for the Western Conference's top seed,
beating the Seattle SuperSonics 107-85 on Tuesday night.
article.headline: Kings improve to an NBA-best 33-6 at home
article.linkText: Kings stay in hunt for West's top seed
article.story: SACRAMENTO, Calif. (AP) -- Vladimir Radmanovic scored 20 points and made a long jumper with 11.9 seconds left to lift the Seattle SuperSonics to a 109-107 preseason win Sunday night over the Sacramento Kings. Rashard Lewis also scored 20 points and Ray Allen had 19 for Seattle (5-2), which sent the Kings (2-4) to their fourth straight loss. Brent Barry added 10 points and seven assists. Bobby Jackson, who led Sacramento with 22 points, missed an off-balance shot in the closing seconds that would have tied the game. Radmanovic, who had 10 fourth-quarter points, made a perimeter shot with 49 seconds left to tie it at 107. Peja Stojakovic had 19 points and eight rebounds for the Kings. Brad Miller scored 15 points and Gerald Wallace had 10. Lewis scored 12 points in the third, helping Seattle rally from an eight-point deficit to tie it at 86. Seattle starting center Jerome James fouled out with 3:51 remaining in the third quarter. He left the game angrily kicking several towels into the stands and finishing with four points and three rebounds. The Kings played without starting center Vlade Divac, who has a sprained ankle. Chris Webber remains sidelined following summer knee surgery.
